hy, those who consumed the spectacle, and the monarchs themselves. In the face of a changing social landscape in their rapidly growing nineteenth-century capital, Russian monarchs reoriented their display of imperial and national representation away from courtiers and toward the urban public. When attacked at mid-century, monarchs retreated from the palace. As they receded, the public claimed the square and the artistic treasures in the Imperial Hermitage before claiming the palace itself. By 1917, the Winter Palace had come to be the essential stage for representing not just monarchy, but the civic life of the empire-nation. What was cataclysmic for the monarchy presented to those who staffed the palace and Hermitage not a disaster, but a new mission, as a public space created jointly by monarch and city passed from the one to the other. This insightful study will appeal to scholars of Russia and general readers interested in Russian history.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMonarchyzRussiaxHistory. 0aPalaceszRussia (Federation)zSaint Petersburg. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aSt. Petersburg, architectural symbols, Russian autocracy, Imperial Hermitage, Russian social landscape.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175800340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501758003423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501758003/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  